{
    "Description": "<h3>Usage</h3><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">file:close()\n</pre><ul><li><code style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 240, 240);\"><strong>file</strong></code>: A valid file handle (typically returned by <code style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 240, 240); color: rgb(37, 144, 205);\"><a href=\"http://localhost:7654/@io.open\" target=\"_blank\">io.open</a></code> or <code style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 240, 240); color: rgb(37, 144, 205);\"><a href=\"http://localhost:7654/@io.popen\" target=\"_blank\">io.popen</a></code>).</li></ul><p><br></p><h3>Notes</h3><ul><li>Files are automatically closed by the Lua garbage collector when their handle is no longer referenced. However, this can be unpredictable.</li><li>Explicitly closing files with <code>file:close()</code> ensures timely resource cleanup.</li><li>Always call <code>close()</code> after you're finished reading from or writing to a file.</li></ul><p><br></p><h3>Returns</h3><ul><li><code>true</code> if the file was closed successfully. <em><u>(bool)</u></em></li><li><code>nil</code> and an error message if the file could not be closed. <em><u>(string)</u></em></li></ul><p><br></p><h3>Example</h3><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">-- Open a file for writing\nlocal W, E = io.open(\"myFile.txt\", \"w\")\nif not W then\n&nbsp; &nbsp;iguana.logError(\"Failed to open file for write: \" .. E)\n&nbsp; &nbsp;return\nend\nW:write(\"Hello, world!\")\nW:close()&nbsp; -- Always close the file after writing\n\n-- Open the file again for reading\nlocal R, E = io.open(\"myFile.txt\", \"r\")\nif not R then\n&nbsp; &nbsp;iguana.logError(\"Failed to open file for read: \" .. E)\n&nbsp; &nbsp;return\nend\nlocal Content = R:read(\"*a\")\nR:close()&nbsp; -- Always close the file after reading\n</pre>",
    "Name": "io:close",
    "Parameters": null,
    "ParameterTable": false,
    "SummaryLine": "Closes an open file handle."
}